description.plain:
Luniz, or Da Luniz, (formerly The LuniTunes) is a platinum-selling hip-hop duo from Oakland, California, formed by rappers Yukmouth and Numskull. After appearing on Dru Down’s single “Ice Cream Man” and Dru’s major label debut album Explicit Game in 1994, the Luniz released their debut album Operation Stackola the following year. The album featured the internationally successful hit “I Got 5 on It”, which would achieve platinum status, and was further propelled by the remix featuring Bay Area rap stars Dru Down, Shock G, Richie Rich, E-40, and Spice 1.

The Luniz would find themselves involved in a beef with Oakland rap legend Too $hort, which was mentioned on the Luniz single “Playa Hata”, leading to $hort’s reply “That’s Why”. After a highly-publicized incident in the Bay Area at KMEL’s Summer Jam concert in 1995, the two squashed the beef and $hort collaborated on the track “Funkin' Over Nuthin'” with the Luniz in 1997 for their second album, Lunitik Muzik.

The crew went on hiatus after the release of their third album Silver & Black in 2002. Yukmouth became a solo artist, dropping his first solo album in 1998. The duo would come back and release the High Timez mixtape in 2015 before dropping their official fourth album, No Pressure, in 2018.

description.plain:
The debut single from the Luniz is a song about pooling money together to get more green—in the form of a fat sack of weed. Yukmouth credits Numskull with devising the song’s concept. With its universal theme, the song took off internationally, reaching the Top 10 on the pop charts of numerous countries, including #1 in the Netherlands. In the US, the song peaked at #8 on the Billboard Hot 100 and #4 on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart as the single reached platinum status. Its success was also propelled by the remix version, which features an all-star cast of Bay Area rappers.

The song was produced by Tone Capone, who replayed a sample of Club Nouveau’s 1986 hit “Why You Treat Me So Bad.” However, a claim was made that Club Nouveau’s sampled riff was actually lifted from the 1986 song “Thinkin' About Ya” by the group Timex Social Club, best known for their hit single “Rumors.” The lead vocals for both Timex Social Club songs featured Michael Marshall, the singer on the chorus of “I Got 5 On It.”

Appropriately, Complex ranked “I Got 5 On It” in the #5 spot on their list of The Best Songs About Weed and #1 on their list of The 50 Greatest Bay Area Rap Songs.

The song received more national attention when it was given a horrorcore remix and featured in the movie trailer for Jordan Peele’s 2019 thriller Us.

description.plain:
On the second single from Operation Stackola, the Luniz address those who envy their newfound success over a sample of Bobby Caldwell’s “What You Won’t Do For Love” and using a re-worked chorus from Chuckii Booker’s single “Games.” The single only peaked at #51 on Billboard’s Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart after “I Got 5 On It” was a Top 5 hit in multiple countries.

The Luniz were receiving some attention for their appearance on Dru Down’s 1994 single “Ice Cream Man” before releasing their own international hit “I Got 5 On It” one year later. Numskull also takes a shot at Bay Area legend Too $hort, which set off a war of words between $hort and the Luniz.  The beef was squashed by the time the second Luniz album was released in 1997, with the three of them collaborating on the track “Funkin' Over Nothin'.”

songs.title: So Much Drama

description.plain:
“So Much Drama” was the B-side on the Luniz’s first single, “I Got 5 On It.” Like the Luniz, Nic Nac was also previously featured on Dru Down’s 1994 major label debut album, Explicit Game.

One drama addressed in this song is with rapper Master P—who lived in the Bay Area around this time—going around calling himself the “Ice Cream Man” after Dru Down and the Luniz released their single “Ice Cream Man” in 1994. Master P would go on to release a song and album called Mr. Ice Cream Man in 1996, and the drama over this issue lasted for years.
